summary:
  - You are building a frontend web app with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and images.
  - The design system and tokens come from Figma MCP.
  - You have an existing manually implemented home page and CSS.
  - Use the home page's HTML structure and CSS styling as the primary reference for consistency.
  - Follow semantic HTML5 and accessibility best practices.
  - Use responsive CSS layouts consistent with the home page style.
  - Write modular, accessible JavaScript based on the patterns used in the home page.
  - Optimize image usage with responsive techniques and alt attributes.
  - Maintain alignment with Figma MCP design tokens and assets.
  
rules:
  - name: Reference Existing Home Page and Styles
    description: Use the existing home page HTML and CSS as the canonical style and structure guide.
    globs:
      - "**/*.html"
      - "**/*.css"
      - "**/*.js"
    instructions:
      - For any new pages, replicate the semantic structure and class naming conventions used on the home page.
      - Follow the CSS style patterns (naming, layout, responsiveness) established in the home page CSS.
      - Mirror JavaScript module patterns and accessibility considerations from the home page code.
      - Ensure consistent header, footer, and navigation components or styles derived from home page.
      - Use the home page as a checklist for responsive breakpoints and interaction patterns.
      
  - name: Semantic HTML and Accessibility
    description: Write accessible, semantic HTML focusing on meaningful markup.
    globs:
      - "**/*.html"
    instructions:
      - Use semantic elements like header, main, footer, nav, section, article.
      - Provide descriptive alt attributes for images.
      - Use ARIA roles where necessary.
      - Preserve logical keyboard navigation.
  
  - name: CSS Styling with Figma MCP Tokens
    description: Consume Figma MCP design tokens for colors, spacing, and typography.
    globs:
      - "**/*.css"
    instructions:
      - Use CSS variables mapped to MCP tokens where possible.
      - Maintain consistency with home page colors and fonts.
      - Use Flexbox and Grid layouts to replicate responsive design.
      - Organize CSS using methodologies like BEM or utility classes consistent with home page.
  
  - name: JavaScript Modularity and Accessibility
    description: Write modular JavaScript enhancing usability and accessibility.
    globs:
      - "**/*.js"
    instructions:
      - Follow the modular JS pattern used on the home page.
      - Handle events with keyboard and screen reader accessibility.
      - Avoid blocking UI; use asynchronous methods where required.
  
  - name: Image Optimization and Responsiveness
    description: Handle images efficiently using responsive and accessible techniques.
    globs:
      - "**/*.{png,jpg,jpeg,gif,svg,webp}"
    instructions:
      - Use srcset and sizes attributes for responsive image loading.
      - Lazy load hidden/offscreen images.
      - Optimize image assets exported from Figma MCP before use.
      - Provide meaningful alt text for all images.

  - name: Figma MCP Synchronization
    description: Keep styles and assets in sync with Figma MCP source data.
    globs:
      - "**/*"
    instructions:
      - Regularly update design tokens if MCP changes.
      - Use MCP exported icons and images with consistent naming conventions.
      - Document any design deviations clearly.
